{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10188,"record_hash":"sha256:96721bd5a68d86668229e80554069682f1acac2bf9a44e96422473ca606130ab","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:50:32.454Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n ## Current Building Blocks\n \n The primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n@@\n That is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\n state to `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+## Current Data Feasibility Check\n+\n+Looking at the live GitMeta database for the `agentlog-turn-storage` branch on\n+2026-05-20, the proposed tools are realistic, but the data shape confirms that\n+they need to be bounded and metadata-heavy.\n+\n+Observed data:\n+\n+- 14 sessions related to the branch\n+- 29 related turns\n+- 7,357 stored transcript records\n+- the largest main session has 16 turns and 6,037 records\n+- the initial backfill turn in that session has 5,371 records\n+- all inspected `previous_turn_key` chains are valid\n+- all inspected turn details resolve back to transcript records\n+- relation index entries verify against `TurnDetail.observed_targets`\n+\n+What works well:\n+\n+- `sessions` discovery is already backed by branch/review/change indexes and\n+  verified against turn details.\n+- `timeline` can be assembled from the turn summary list plus turn details.\n+- `records` can render authoritative order from `TurnDetail.records`.\n+- source metadata already exposes agent, provider, model, and tool version.\n+- environment snapshots expose observed branches/changes/reviews and worktree\n+  path counts.\n+\n+Gaps to account for:\n+\n+- Related sessions are not the same as one main session. The real branch already\n+  includes the main thread plus sidecar/subagent sessions.\n+- There is no reliable parent/child session linkage in GitMeta today. Sidecar\n+  sessions can be inferred from timing, record counts, or prompts, but not\n+  proven structurally.\n+- `TurnDetail.records` stores record hashes, not per-turn ordinals. Record\n+  hydration is still feasible by scanning the session transcript once and\n+  resolving hashes, but pagination should use the ordinal position within\n+  `TurnDetail.records`, not the provider `record_index`.\n+- Provider `record_index` is sparse. In the largest backfill, records span\n+  source indexes `3..8911` but contain 5,371 captured records.\n+- Current `find_related_sessions` returns sessions in key order, not recency\n+  order. For catch-up, related sessions should be sorted by latest activity.\n+- Current timeline hydration returns full records for selected turns. That is\n+  too heavy for agent orientation; timeline should return metadata and small\n+  previews, while `records` handles bounded transcript windows.\n+- Naive latest-user previews can surface internal provider events such as\n+  subagent notifications. Those records should remain available in `records`,\n+  but `sessions` and `timeline` previews should either label or skip them.\n+- Observed branch/review/change targets show relation evidence, not ownership.\n+  A branch can be observed by background review or sidecar work.\n+\n+This means the minimal tools are feasible without a storage rewrite, but the\n+read layer should be careful: sort by recency, expose match evidence, keep\n+timeline light, and page records by turn-local position.\n \n ## Design Bias\n \n The agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:50:32.454Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}